sudoers file (/etc/sudoers)
Controls who can run commands as root using sudo
Always edit using: sudo visudo

Syntax:

user  host=(run_as_user)  command

Example:

rajat ALL=(ALL) ALL
rajat ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL
NOPASSWD → no password required
sshd_config (/etc/ssh/sshd_config)
Configuration of SSH server (remote login)

Important settings:

Port 22
PermitRootLogin no
PasswordAuthentication yes

Restart SSH after changes:

sudo systemctl restart sshd
.bashrc (~/.bashrc)
User shell configuration file
Runs when terminal opens
Used for aliases and environment variables

Example:

alias ll='ls -alF'
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17

Apply changes:

source ~/.bashrc

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++


`sudo cat /etc/ssh/sshd_config`  →  display SSH server configuration file (read-only)

`cat /etc/group`  →  display all groups in the system

`id john`  →  show UID, GID, and groups of user john

`cat /etc/passwd`  →  display user account details

`cat /etc/shadow`  →  display encrypted user passwords (root only)

`whoami`  →  show current logged-in user

`groups`  →  show groups of current user

`id`  →  show UID, GID, and groups of current user


`sudo usermod -aG <group-name> <user-name>`  →  add user to a group (append without removing existing groups)

                                      **Example:**
                                      `sudo usermod -aG sudo rajat`

sudo groupadd <group-name> → create a new group

sudo gpasswd -d <username> <group-name> → remove user from a group























